    <!-- message -->
    <div align="left" id="post_message_380946">To quote Steven Colbair (sp) as he stormed off the stage as the final results of the mid-term election were posted, &quot;The terrorists have won!!!&quot;  Only in this case its the hand me everything on a silver platter because I don't want to work for it crowd who's winning.<br />
<br />
I'm absolutely stunned by this.  Through all the bugs and issues we've experienced, I've..ahem &quot;stayed the course&quot;, but if this is implemented in any way, shape, form or fashion, I'm out.  <br />
<br />
They did exactly this in EQ2, to appeal to the casual gamers that didn't want a challenging MMO.  They had the shard system that returned EXP when you retrieved it.  At first it was a fairly interesting system, yea you had all of your gear, so it wasn't a true CR, but hey it did have those elements.  They eventually removed that all together and reduced the cost of dying to a very laughable excuse of &quot;the sting of death&quot;.  To top it off they added the mechanic that allows you to &quot;sleep off debt&quot; where if you avoided playing that toon for a few days, all of your debt would fade away.<br />
<br />
And you know what?  Because of that, death was a traveling mechanism for me.  I'd simply strip off all my gear (as there was a 10% durability hit that your gear would take when you died, but eventually they all but removed that as well), shout LEEROY JENKINS!!!  Then off myself somehow.  Ironically, I found out that some of my toons were remarkably resilient and took a bit longer to die than I had anticipated.  At any rate, you catch my drift, it made death a joke and a lot of people (most of the player base in fact) had 0 fear of dying.  After a while, it made it difficult to tell the truly crappy players from the really good ones who were just goofing off because they didn't care anymore and wanted to see what would happen if...<br />
<br />
Don't get me wrong, I'm in no way a machinist who enjoys the pain of a multiple body corpse run that inevitably leads to more deaths, but you can not argue that the expierience of that or the simple threat of it does drive you to improve your skills within the game.  And the player that is committed to improving themselves will be your long term subscriber, not the guy who wants to beat the game inside their first month's subscription window so that they can cancel and spend their allowance elsewhere.  Perhaps I'm just narrowminded and am not looking at the larger share of the current gaming market, but to me it doesn't make good buisness sense to piss off loyal, long term subscribers in order to acquire many who only play/subscribe sporatically...whenever there is new content to chew through in a couple of days.<br />
<br />
Edit: Sorry that was a bit longerwinded than intended.  Just the whole dumbing down of...well everything gets to me.  An ounce of common sense and effort can go a very long way.</div>
    <!-- / message -->
    
    
